I had heard good things about this, so I went into it expecting to be entertained. I was. It is a solid, well choreographed, tightly edited action movie. Unlike most action movies lately, this one did not get bogged down by a long running time, featured no pop culture references, and delivered the goods. I understand that the directors were former stunt doubles for Keanu Reeves, which would explain why the action sequences are so awesome. It's also interesting, considering the fact that Keanu gave up a large chunk of his paycheck from the Matrix movies to his stunt team, which maybe allowed them to step out and make this movie. Good fun.

I had read the book, and went into this feeling a bit nervous about how much it would glorify war. I was really impressed with how Eastwood left the political message ambiguous, so that if you are inclined to view this as a celebration of Chris Kyle, you can, but if you prefer to see it as a depiction of how awful war is, that is also available. It's rare to see a mainstream movie that is brave enough and competent enough to maturely tackle this topic. I wouldn't say it was perfect, but quite solid, and a few years ago, who would've guessed that Bradley Cooper would turn into such a decent actor?

I had followed the story of Linklater making this movie for years before it was released, and was really interested in the process of filming and editing a movie over the course of a young boy's life. That said, I was still a little wary of actually watching it, because I worried that it would be boring or meandering. There were so many ways that it could have gone wrong, but in the end I should have had more faith. This was a really insightful show about families and childhood, and a beautiful portrait of central Texas. It gave me a lot to think about, and was on my mind for days after I watched it. All of the performances were great, but Ellar Koltrane really had to carry the film, and he did. This is my pick for best director for 2014.

Man, where to begin with this one...When I first saw it in theaters, I left the theater thinking, "what on earth was that?" It had some great moments, but then it took a weird turn into the realm of animation, where it was difficult for me to distinguish between dream and reality. Since I very much dislike dream sequences (because it undermines the real and present stake of the story), I grew tired, thinking the entire movie was a dream sequence. Leaving the theater, I was perplexed about what I thought... I never thought I would want to watch this movie again. I felt unfulfilled after watching it. Then weeks went by, and I kept thinking about this movie over and over. I started making connections between the film's vision of the future, and seeing perfect illustrations of the future of capitalism, escapism, and even a display of what I might argue as a natural progression towards a dictatorship of the proletariat (and then some). It doesn't even dive into the rights or wrongs of such systems, but presents it as just the way it is. It's strange to have a movie I was a little bored with occupy so much of my mental energy. 6 months later, it comes available on Amazon prime, and by that time I was desperate to see it again. Watching it a second time, holy crap did my entire view of the film change. I was able to easily distinguish between dream and reality, and was captivated from beginning to end, and it blew me away. Interestingly, I don't think I could recommend this movie to anyone, but I just loved watching it a second time (and I suspect many times over), it's unfortunate that I needed the first time to establish my bearings in order to appreciate this film, but I think that was intentional, as the main character couldn't distinguish between reality and dreaming too. Regardless, just brilliant. Also, Robin Wright moved up several notches on my favorite actress list for this one.

I really had zero expectations for this movie, which seemed like a stupid Hollywood gimmick. I should have had more faith in Soderbergh, who I don't always like, but who at least I always respect. This movie is my definition of a movie-movie -- a fun, flashy, well-made time waster. I love it. I've probably rewatched Ocean's Eleven more than any other movie in the last 15 years. I love that Brad Pitt's character is always eating. I love how George Clooney's character is introduced at his parole hearing, with a static shot on him the entire time. I love that when he gets released from prison, the clothes he gets back are a tuxedo. I love that Brad Pitt's character is introduced teaching poker to a bunch of B-list celebrities, who are mobbed for autographs as they leave the club while he just walks by. I love the music. I love Ruben's character. I love the friendship between the thieves. I love the brothers from Provo, and their stupid arguments. Any recommendations of other fun heist movies with careful attention to details would be appreciated.

Kim and I decided to randomly drop by an arthouse cinema when we first lived in Washington DC, and see the first film released from Afghanistan after the fall of the Taliban. I don't know what I expected, but this film left the entire audience silent as the credits rolled. Nobody moved, nobody spoke. We just sat there, drained by the experience. Incredibly eye opening as to what it would be like as a woman in such a repressive culture. I'm not sure I could watch it again, but I highly recommend it to anyone who wants to better understand Afghanistan.

Saw this with a friend at a film festival in Chile. It was really interesting to learn about the small-town bullfighting culture in rural Mexico. Lots of alcoholism, desperation and poverty. This film has led to a firm policy (12 years and counting) of not attending this kind of movie in the theater. What do I mean by 'this kind of movie'? Any film which features a recently divorced female protagonist who must go on a some kind of journey to discover who she is. "But wait!", I can hear you saying, "what about Wild?" I have heard good things about it, and I will eventually get around to watching it, but I just haven't trusted Hollywood to do this kind of story in a meaningful way. We need more female protagonists who already know who they are, and who are not defined by their break-up. We don't need more movies about women who must be shown how to live, now that they don't have a man. Especially since they are usually shown how to live by the next man, whose wisdom is established by his foreign accent.

One of these bizarre cases where Hollywood makes two identical movies in the same year. If John Wick is A Bugs Life, then The Equalizer is Antz. Or maybe if John Wick is Full Metal Jacket, The Equalizer is Platoon. Or Tombstone and Wyatt Earp? Capote and Infamous? Anyway, this is also about a widowed bad ass who promised his dead wife he would not be "that man" anymore, but who is called out of retirement to kill everyone in the Russian mob, using a particular set of skills. I enjoyed it because it was Denzel Washington creatively killing people using tools at Home Depot, and because it looked so much like a Tony Scott film (RIP). Still, John Wick is the superior film, with regards to pacing, action and overall badassery.

Kingsman does a pretty good job of announcing its intentions when Colin Firth first meets Samuel L. Jackson, but perhaps that should have been in the marketing. I was expecting more of a slick, spy thriller with a few jokes, and instead I got a weirdly campy, yet ultraviolent, throwback to the worst Bond era. It's not that it was without its pleasures (the church scene was wild), but overall the tone was weird. Jackson's lisp, the amputee henchwoman, the maligned Swedish princess -- there were a lot of gags that they went for that fell flat for me. Still, it wasn't just another Hollywood formulaic film, and you've got to give Matthew Vaughn credit for making big films with big names that somehow don't conform.

I have to admit, I went into this one looking to dislike it, but it won me over and overall I have to say it was pretty good. Compared to the first one, Age of Ultron has much more emotional weight, something that was glaringly missing from the first one. It was a little more intense, a little funnier, a little more moving. It has a few surprises that they amazingly kept out of the trailers and are the highlights I think. On the bad side, it still suffers from the main thing the first one suffered from which is that many of the fights/battles had little to no weight or nothing at stake. The foes were faceless droids, we didn't care that they got punched and rarely felt like the avengers were in real danger. But the small dramatic moments between characters peppered throughout the movie made it work, I enjoyed the film the most when they weren't being super and instead just interacting with each other.

When all aspects of a film come together in the right why, there is something harmonious that just makes me smile. With Ex Machina, writer/director Alex Garland had a specific vision, and was able to pull it off gorgeously. There are plenty of knowing references to classic sci fi questions, and just the right amount of future gazing. Garland brilliantly made use of an existing location in Norway to keep costs down while making it seem like a top tier movie in terms of budget. The three (only three!!) lead actors in this film nailed the tone, exactly conveying what Garland wanted, when he wanted it, which kept me constantly guessing at the next reveal in the story. No matter how far ahead I thought I had the story figured out, Garland was smart enough to take it just a bit further. My only quibble with the film is the ending, which went 5 minutes past what was needed.

Wow! Mind blowingly good. I thought it looked like some lame outer space movie from the previews, but based on Ryan Barlow's recommendation, I watched it. Best movie I've seen in a long time!

A lot of Fury was great. Opening shot as a western, with a horse eventually wandering between destroyed tanks; unflinching glimpses at what war requires young men to become; a (single) realistic portrayal of a tank battle; etc. It loses a lot of the goodwill it has built up in its third act where our heroes make their cliched last stand against the cartoonish SS squadron, but I did enjoy the last moment of humanity that Ayers allowed from a young German soldier. Solid film, almost great.
It felt like more like a parody of the first than a sequel. Still, was good for some laughs.

What a ham fisted metaphor, and what a bore. How in the hell did this get 95% on Rotten Tomatoes? I am predisposed to like dystopian films and science fiction in general, and this thing lost me in the first few minutes of its ridiculous premise, propelled by bizarre, incomprehensible characters.
First Ghost Protocol and now this. Brad Bird needs to stick with animation. Was very let down by this.
I will need to re-watch this one. Good non-traditional horror film.
You definitely get to feel what torture is like.

Not one to watch with kids. Surprised it didn't earn an "r" rating. But man, what a good movie. Once again, blown away by Miyazaki's execution, and the way he builds his antagonists, if you could even call them that. Best execution of a film with an "environmentalist" plot.
Really enjoyed this movie! I got to get me a pair of those boots! (Note to sons, great birthday present! Hint, hint)

Nirvana fans, or any child of the 90s, watch this documentary. It was beautifully made, with the animation, music and lack of narrator commentary. A very intimate and fascinating insight into Cobain, showing what made him who he was. I'll never listen to the music in the same way.

Loved it. Oyelowo was very impressive as King. I was surprised at how natural the speeches seemed, given that the screenwriter had to invent them, due to not having the rights to the actual speeches. I do wish that the ending credits would have had actual historical photos, but overall I thought this was really well made, informative and important.
Tired of the found footage genre, but I really enjoyed this ET ripoff. Kids loved it.
great movie
A guilty pleasure for me.
Went in blind and loved it. Slow to start, unless you like a deep dive into the food industry life. Nice, warm, fuzzy, father-son story, but the food and snark made it for me.

Jurassic World brought back some of the magic from the original. It's certainly better than the second and third installments. It surpasses the first even in some areas like how I didn't want the kids to die in this one. Chris Pratt is a great leading man, and Bryce Dallas Howard wasn't nearly as unbearable as I thought she would be from the trailers. I thought it all worked, and I really wasn't expecting it to.

Original Mad Max movies are not my thing, but when I heard great reviews of this one I hoped for the best. Dry as the originals. They chases looks good, but I couldn't care less about the characters. I would have liked to see more of the world they are living, but maybe there isn't much left. In the film where everyone is little crazy I would have liked Mad Max much crazier!
Couldn't love movie characters more! Tough subject and great supporting characters makes this even better. Tear alert!

A modern masterpiece. One hour and 46 minutes of concise storytelling. Funny, violent, through provoking, global, terse, exciting. I love this film. If you don't like this, then you and I have a completely different idea of what makes good cinema.
I really enjoyed this! Such a clever story. Emma Thompson continues to amaze me as an actress.
loved it. need to watch it again to pick up on more clues!
just badass all around
really had fun with this!
not the best but didn't hate it. good gore. very saw-esque
Fun movie! Just the right blend of scary and humorous. The more I see Chris Pratt the more I like his acting.

I wish Jim Carrey would do more roles like this. There are so many ideas being addressed in this movie: commercialism, power of media, authenticity, reality tv, product placement, etc. I think it's brilliant, and an endearing watch to boot.

Just re-watched this last night with my kids and I still love it. The animation is beautiful and the story is mesmerizing. The pacing of Studio Ghibli movies is much slower than what we are used to, but somehow Miyazaki keeps you glued to the screen. Sprited Away was the first one of the bunch that I saw several years back and I rented it from Netflix out of mild curiosity back when I had movies delivered by mail. I couldn't stop thinking about it for days and it sent me searching for more like it. Of course, only Studio Ghibli is like Sudio Ghibli!
Wow. An actually contender against The Incredibles for favorite Pixar film. A movie about emotions playing with my emotions. Brilliant.

While it starts off rather awkwardly with some cheesy dialogue, Jurassic World is crowd-pleasing, thrilling, scary (maybe not) and suspenseful that is loaded with dinosaur nostalgia. Pratt is decent though I liked him better in the guardian movie. Howard is a cold bitch that is very difficult to warm up to, but redeem herself by the end of the movie. This is enjoyable if you come in without any expectations and don't try to make sense of anything... Just enjoy the darn thing.

San Andreas is as predictable and cliche as any disaster movie. The Rock is actually getting better at acting, still cheesy but better for sure... I am still not over the opening scene but if you want to enjoy this one you will have to get over the cheese factor :)
Pleasantly surprised. Super fun.

I really wanted to like this more than I did, but it was winking to the past terminators a little too much and Emilia Clarke was terribly miscast. I'm blown away that James Cameron had anything to do with the screen play. A fun watch, but I'd probably rank the terminators like so: Terminator 2, Terminator 1, Terminator 3, Genisys, Salvation
I sat down to an almost empty theater and as it was starting, I thought to my self, "what am i doing here." It was ridiculous but I didn't hate it.

a million times better than the remake. PLEASE recognize the genius that is Dudley Moore and Sir John Gielgud.

i know I'm in the minority on this but here's what I didn't like about it: the characters tell you what's going to happen, then it happens then another character recaps what just happened. Oh my stop it!! I couldn't enjoy the story. Dead horse....here's your beating.

feel good rom com. Don Lake and Bonnie Hunt are a dynamic writing team. I love their style. I also love Chicago movies for so many reasons. The familiar locations, the hometown casts and the feeling of being in on an inside joke.

This was a day one purchase for me! I saw it once and it stuck with me for weeks. It's got so many good things going for it.

This is the only time I can think of that I've fallen asleep at a movie theater (and I've seen "Tinker Tailer Soldier Spy" and "Tree of Life" in theaters). A movie dedicated to cheap jokes and a weak plot, I just couldn't pay attention.
Not as great as I hoped it to be. Bad guy was boring. Looked great but it action went many times too messy to follow. Still I have high hopes for this bunch for the future.

I wasn't sure of the tone of this before I saw it and having seen it I'm still not sure. It's an unusual blend of gross reality and quirk that is just right for Wiig.

This was better watching a second time. I'm a big Mike Judge fan, but could never got on board with this one. Even though I appreciate his message, it's super frustrating to listen to every person talk in the film aside from the two actors, and even though that's the point, it doesn't make it any less frustrating.
I had never heard of Amy Schumer before this, and while I found her really funny, I think John Cena stole the show. In typical Judd Apatow fashion, this was funny, crude, and a little moving.

I really wanted to love this one, but instead I just enjoyed it. I enjoyed watching some cool stunts and great action sequences, but I didn't feel any emotional weight to any of the scenes like I did in the first or the 3rd Mission:Impossible. It was fun, but I was really hoping for it to be great. Here's how I'd rank the MI franchise: 3, 1, 4, 5, 2.
One more thing, I was so put off by the score I would have sworn that it was by Danny Elfman (it was Lalo Schifrin). It felt so clunky, and campy, straight out of spiderman 3.
Some big laughs, Sandra bullock was a meh Villain, it started super strong then got a little week at times.

Marvel did it again. Loved the books when I was a kid and the film didn't disappoint. Paul Rudd played Paul Rudd playing Ant-man which was great because Paul Rudd is awesome.

Pixar is back! I loved this film. We just moved our kids to a new country last year, and this was an excellent film to watch together to help them process some of the emotions they've had over the year. I still think Wall-E is my favorite from Pixar, but this one is right up there with The Incredibles, Finding Nemo and Monster's Inc.

The romantic comdey genre is such a dead, sterile area that it is always refreshing to see one that at least has good intentions and a story to tell. This movie is fantastic. Recommended for fans of time travel movies and sci-fi. The plot kind of sneaks up on you and by the time you realize what is going on, you are totally invested. The cinematography is well done and the entire film has a very indie feel to it.

I didn't expect to enjoy this film, but the dialogue was good and the acting was top-notch (though I don't understand what inspired Sam Jackson to do the accent). The movie attempts to point out all the "flaws" and "tropes" of spy movies for the sake of comedy, but I feel that it falls into a few of it's own cliches and tropes. These still kind of feel refreshing because of the application of a modern world, but there's still something familiar about the film that kept me from rating it higher.
Towards the end, the story drags and once you know where it's going it doesn't hold the attention.
Finally a petty throwback that wasn't a shell of it's former self. It isn't as good as the first, but I felt like it was worthy of calling itself a sequel.
Leto and Matthew are great actors that make this movie. Predictable yes, but really great acting!

A fantastic subversion of action films and cinema's varied macho archetypes. Much more a Cormac McCarthy film than a Ridley Scott film.

Really good. This is the kind of show that would have been terrible if made by the studio system -- teenagers fighting aliens. But Joe Cornish took the premise seriously, added some social commentary, and it came out a fun, unique alien movie. The young cast was excellent, the special effects were ingeniously simple, and everything looked great
